{{Use British English|date=May 2012}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}} '''The World's 50 Best Restaurants''' is a list produced by UK media company [[William Reed Business Media]], which originally appeared in the British magazine ''[[Restaurant (magazine)|Restaurant]]'', based on a poll of international [[chef]]s, [[restaurateur]]s, [[gourmand]]s and [[restaurant critic]]s. In addition to the main ranking, the organisation awards a series of special prizes for individuals and restaurants, including the One To Watch award, the Lifetime Achievement Award and the Chefs' Choice Award, the latter based on votes from the fifty head chefs from the restaurants on the previous year's list. Often working as a barometer of global gastronomic trends, the list showcases a variety of cuisines from all over the world<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theworlds50best.com/|title=The World's 50 Best Restaurants|website=The World's 50 Best Restaurants|access-date=2018-08-07}}</ref>. The top restaurants have sometimes been forerunners of [[molecular gastronomy]]. Most of the restaurants serve [[haute cuisine]], which is characterized by the meticulous preparation and careful presentation of food.
The first place on the list has been dominated by [[elBulli]] and [[Noma (restaurant)|Noma]]. In 2002 and 2006‚Äì2009, elBulli was determined to be the world's best restaurant, winning more times than any other restaurant.{{r|XSECN}} In 2010, Noma received the first place award. It was maintained in 2011 and again in 2012.{{r|2012 awards}} After defending its title for the third time, chef [[Ren√© Redzepi]] said that 1,204 customers were wait-listed for the evening, compared to 14 customers from two years before.{{r|QdZ8I}} However, in 2013 [[El Celler de Can Roca|El Celler De Can Roca]] took over the first position before Noma regained it in 2014. In 2018, [[Osteria Francescana]] regained the crown it had held in 2016, after dropping to second in 2017, when [[Eleven Madison Park]] topped the poll.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/worlds-best-restaurants-2018/index.html |title=World's 50 best restaurants for 2018 announced |author=Barry Neild |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=20 June 2018}}</ref>
== History == The list originated as a one-off stunt by the staff of ''Restaurant'' magazine, who came up with the idea at the [[Shaston Arms]] public house in London's [[Carnaby Street]].{{r|NY}} It was more successful than they expected and soon became established as a major event in the culinary world.{{r|NY}}
The World's 50 Best Restaurants list is compiled from the votes of the "World‚Äôs 50 Best Restaurants Academy", a group of 26 panels established to make the ranking<ref name=":0" />.{{r|JrySP}} The world is divided into regions, with a chairperson in each region appointed for their knowledge of their part of the restaurant world. These chairs each selected a voting panel of 40 members, who every year cast thousands of votes.
There is no list of nominees; each member of the international voting panel votes for their own personal choice of ten restaurants. Up to six votes can be cast for restaurants in the voter's own region, while at least four must go to restaurants outside of the home region.<ref name=":0" /> No voting member is allowed to vote for their own restaurant, or one in which they have an economic interest, and voters must have eaten in the restaurants they nominate within the past 18 months. The integrity of the voting process and the resulting list is adjudicated by global consultancy firm Deloitte.<ref name=":0" />
The criteria are different from those of the ''[[Michelin Guide]]'' or other guides, which has allowed restaurants like [[Momofuku Ssam Bar]], [[Asador Etxebarri]] and [[St. John (restaurant)|St. John]] to hold their own among the [[Molecular gastronomy|molecular]] or [[traditional cuisine]] of restaurants such as [[The Fat Duck]], [[Les Ambassadeurs (restaurant)|Les Ambassadeurs]] or [[The French Laundry]].
